# CURSOR RULES for FREHG2 Development

## ⚠️ CRITICAL: Read Before Writing Any Code

You are working on **FREHG2** — a production-grade surface water - groundwater - solute transport coupled numerical model. This is NOT a prototype, NOT a simplified demo, and NOT a proof-of-concept. Every line of code you write must be production-quality.

**Current repository state**: this repo starts from the upgrade plan, selected docs, legacy Frehg/SERGHEI sources, and reference data. Root Frehg2 infrastructure (`src/`, `include/`, `tests/`, root CMake) may be skeletal or newly created. Follow Phase -1, Phase 0, and Phase 1 of `INTEGRATED_PLAN.md` before solver implementation. Phase 0 is mandatory: reconcile plan/rules/schema/source paths/benchmark references/dependency paths/GPU policy before writing production solver code.

---

## 🚨 Anti-Shortcut Rules (Violations = Failed Task)

### 1. NO STUBS EVER
- `return 0;`, `return {};`, `throw std::runtime_error("TODO")` are FORBIDDEN in production code
- If you don't know how to implement something, ASK — don't stub it
- Stubs are only allowed in `tests/` for mock objects, NEVER in `src/`

### 2. ALL CODE MUST BE REACHABLE FROM main.cpp
- If you implement a class that is only used in tests but NOT called from `Orchestrator::run()` or `SimulationDriver::run()`, it is INCOMPLETE
- Every public method must have a code path from `main()` → ... → that method
- Test-only wiring (BC applied in test fixture but not in production driver) is a BUG

### 3. "It compiles" is NOT Acceptance
- Every test must assert a NUMERICAL BOUND (e.g., `REQUIRE(error < 1e-6)`)
- A test that merely constructs an object and does not assert on output values is USELESS
- "No crash" is not a passing test

### 4. Boundary Conditions MUST Be Applied at EVERY Time Step
- If a BC is read from config and applied only at initialization, that is a BUG
- BCs must be applied inside the solver loop at every time step
- Polygon BC is the PRIMARY path from Phase 12 onwards; legacy `bc_type` is DEPRECATED

### 5. LINEAR ALGEBRA GOES THROUGH A BACKEND-AGNOSTIC INTERFACE (NO DMDA)
- All physics/assembly code talks to the `LinearSolver` / `SparseSystem` interface (Plan P2.5), NEVER to `Mat`, `Vec`, `KSP`, `DM`/`DMDA`, or any Trilinos/Ginkgo type directly
- There is **NO PETSc `DMDA`**. The model owns its data layout (flat halo-padded `Kokkos::View`s, see `Grid`) and its parallel layout/halo exchange (`DomainDecomposition` + `MpiComm`, Plan P2.3–P2.4)
- The default backend is `PetscLinearSolver`: build matrices with `MatCreate` + `MatSetType(MATMPIAIJ)` (or `MATAIJKOKKOS` on GPU) + explicit `MatMPIAIJSetPreallocation` computed from `DomainDecomposition::stencilColumns` — NOT from a `DMDA`
- `MatCreateSeqAIJ` / `MatCreateSeqBAIJ` are FORBIDDEN in `src/`. `DMCreateMatrix` and `DMDACreate*` are FORBIDDEN. `PETSC_COMM_SELF` is FORBIDDEN in solver code; use `PETSC_COMM_WORLD`. **Serial = one rank** (`mpirun -n 1`), which is the bring-up path used before MPI/halo work
- Matrix/vector types are selected through PETSc options (`-mat_type`, `-vec_type`) inside the PETSc backend so the same code runs on CPU and future GPU PETSc builds

### 6. Memory Safety is NON-NEGOTIABLE
- All arrays MUST use `Kokkos::View` (no `new[]`, `delete[]`, `malloc`, `free`)
- PETSc objects MUST use RAII wrappers (custom `PetscDeleter` or wrapper classes)
- No raw pointers in production code
- EVERY test must pass under `-fsanitize=address` or `valgrind --leak-check=full`

### 7. Compiler Warnings = Errors
- Build flags: `-Wall -Wextra -Werror -Wno-unused-parameter`
- Zero warnings allowed. If a warning is unavoidable, document with `#pragma GCC diagnostic`
- If you see a warning during build, FIX IT — do not ignore it

### 8. Missing or Broken Capabilities MUST Be Implemented, Not "Verified"
- Phase 0 of `INTEGRATED_PLAN.md` maps missing, broken, or unmapped capabilities before solver work starts
- If a task says "Implement or verify X" and P0 marks X as missing, broken, or unmapped, you MUST implement or map X before relying on it
- "Verify it compiles" is NOT fixing it

### 9. Parallel Correctness
- Every function that accesses neighbor cell data MUST use the model-owned halo exchange (`DomainDecomposition::haloExchange` / `MpiComm::haloExchange{2,3}D`) before reading ghosts — there is NO `DMGlobalToLocal` because there is no `DMDA`
- Reading a neighbor cell without a prior halo exchange is a DATA RACE
- Bring up and prove the algorithm SERIALLY first (one rank), then introduce decomposition/halo as a gated refactor (Plan P4.S/P5.S). Test on 1, 2, and 4 MPI ranks — if it only works on 1 rank after the parallel stage, it's BROKEN
- MPI rank-count equivalence is a gate: same executable/backend on 1/2/4 ranks must agree to L2 < 1e-10

### 10. GPU Code Must Be Kokkos-Compliant
- All device code must be in `KOKKOS_LAMBDA` or `Kokkos::parallel_for`
- NO `std::cout`, `printf`, `std::vector`, or file I/O inside Kokkos lambdas
- NO `MatSetValues` inside a `KOKKOS_LAMBDA` (PETSc functions are not GPU-callable)
- Physics kernels emit COO triplets to `SparseSystem::addRow` (host) / `addCOO` (device); the Kokkos→PETSc staging (`MatSetValues` HostSpace on CPU, `MatSetValuesCOO` on GPU) lives ONLY inside the PETSc backend (`src/linear/backends/`), never in physics code
- **Numerical-first, Kokkos/GPU-last (sequencing).** A per-cell numerical treatment (IC, BC/polygon, soil parameters, sources, coupling/async exchange, solute) is needed regardless of the execution skeleton, so implement and serially validate it as PLAIN serial/MPI loops in its own phase FIRST. Kokkos parallelization (Plan Phase 9) and the GPU bridge (Plan Phase 10) are the SINGLE, LAST passes that convert the complete kernel surface at once; they add NO new numerical behavior (gate = bit-identical CPU/OpenMP reproduction of the serial reference). Do NOT Kokkos-ify a kernel in an earlier phase, and do NOT defer a numerical feature until after parallelization
- Current macOS machine cannot run CUDA GPU tests. Write GPU-capable code now; label GPU tests `gpu`, skip them locally, and defer real execution to future Linux/NVIDIA validation. GPU execution must not block completion of the production CPU/OpenMP model on this machine.

---

## 📋 Coding Standards

### C++ Style
- C++20 standard (`CMAKE_CXX_STANDARD 20`, no extensions); this matches the language level modern Kokkos targets and the `g++-15` toolchain. Kokkos must be built with `Kokkos_CXX_STANDARD=20`. Do NOT use C++23-only features without explicit approval
- `#include <Kokkos_Core.hpp>` at the top of every file using Kokkos. `#include <petsc.h>` (and any PETSc/solver-library header) is allowed ONLY inside `src/linear/backends/` — physics code includes the `LinearSolver`/`SparseSystem` interface headers instead
- Use `real` typedef (defined in the core Frehg2 type header selected by P0/P1, e.g. `define.hpp`) for floating-point (default: `double`)
- Function names: `lowerCamelCase` (e.g., `computeExchangeRate`)
- Class names: `UpperCamelCase` (e.g., `SweSolver`)
- Member variables: trailing underscore (e.g., `state_`)
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`

### File Organization
- Header files: `include/frehg2/**/*.hpp` or the P0/P1-approved public header layout
- Implementation: `src/**/*.cpp`
- Tests: `tests/**/test_*.cpp`
- Every `.cpp` file must have a corresponding header file (except `main.cpp`)

### Error Handling
- Use `PetscErrorCode` and `CHKERRQ(ierr)` for PETSc calls
- Use `Kokkos::abort()` for device-side errors
- Use C++ exceptions for host-side errors (but NOT inside Kokkos lambdas)
- Error messages must be CLEAR: say WHAT failed, WHERE, and WHY

---

## 🏗️ Architecture Rules

### Data Flow (EVERY Time Step)
```
1. Kokkos parallel_for: compute local stencil coefficients
   → Store in Kokkos::View (dual-space for host/device)
2. Emit COO triplets (global_row, global_col, value) to the SparseSystem interface:
   CPU: SparseSystem::addRow(...)   (backend stages via MatSetValues on HostSpace)
   GPU: SparseSystem::addCOO(...)   (backend stages via MatSetValuesCOO)
   (global indices come from DomainDecomposition::globalRow / ::stencilColumns)
3. LinearSolver::solve(A, b, x)      (default backend wraps PETSc KSP; no DMDA)
4. Kokkos parallel_for: update state from solution vector
```

### Linear Solver (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
- All global solves go through the `LinearSolver` / `SparseSystem` interface (Plan P2.5). Physics code never sees `Mat`/`Vec`/`KSP`/`DM` or any solver-library type
- **PETSc `KSP` is the default and the ONLY currently sanctioned production backend.** NO hand-rolled / custom Krylov implementations anywhere (the "serial" path is one-rank PETSc, not a custom solver)
- Trilinos (Tpetra/Belos/MueLu), Ginkgo, and KokkosKernels are **evaluation candidates only** (Plan Phase P2B). Adopting any of them as production requires updating THIS file and the plan's "Linear Solver" design principle first
- Kokkidio is NOT a sparse/linear solver (it is an Eigen↔Kokkos kernel bridge); it may only be considered for local per-cell kernels, never as a solver backend
- Solver type selectable at runtime via `-ksp_type` (default: `cg` for SPD, `gmres` for non-symmetric); serial bring-up uses a deterministic direct option (`-pc_type lu`)

### SWE / RE Legacy Parity & Serial-First Sequencing (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
- **Serial-first**: prove the legacy-exact algorithm on ONE rank (flat `Kokkos::View`s + one-rank `PetscLinearSolver`, no `DomainDecomposition` halo) BEFORE introducing MPI/parallel layout. Separate numerical fidelity (A) from parallel re-expression (B); never debug both at once. See Plan P4.S (4a→4f) and P5.S (5a→5e)
- **Instrumentation-first**: the legacy dump tools (`scripts/dump_legacy_swe_matrix.c`, `scripts/dump_legacy_re_matrix.c`) and substep dump hooks are a HARD prerequisite, built BEFORE the time loop. Building/running the legacy code is a hard prerequisite (Plan P0.7.1)
- Phase 4 is complete only when the legacy-exact `b1-sw` gate passes serially (L2 < 1e-6), then holds rank-count equivalence; passing unit tests or `b0-lake` alone is NOT enough
- Any behavior used by `legacy/frehg/src/shallowwater.c` in the `b1-sw` path belongs in Phase 4 (time stepping, rainfall interpolation/reset, face geometry, bottom drag, wet/dry logic, waterfall correction, velocity BCs, output cadence). RE (Phase 5) is split into sub-gates: constitutive / single-solve / predictor-corrector / adaptive-dt, each with element-wise legacy parity (not only the loose Warrick gate)
- Before debugging the full benchmark directly, add or use substep parity tests against instrumented legacy dumps for geometry, source timing, drag/momentum, matrix/RHS, solve state, and velocity BC outputs
- Do NOT loosen the `b1-sw` / `b2-gw` tolerances or move required behavior to later phases to declare a phase complete

### Boundary Conditions (Phase 12+)
- Polygon-based BC is the PRIMARY path
- Legacy `bc_type` integer arrays are DEPRECATED (will be removed in Phase 23)
- Every BC must be applied at EVERY time step, not just initialization

### Output Format (Phase 3+)
- Output goes through a backend-agnostic `OutputWriter` interface; HDF5 is the default implementation (netCDF/ADIOS2 may be added behind the same interface). Legacy text output is DEPRECATED
- Every output file MUST embed provenance: git SHA, resolved-config hash, units per field, build/backend info
- Visualization: emit an XDMF sidecar (or CF-conformant metadata) so ParaView/VisIt can open results directly
- The parallel-write vs. compression trade-off is explicit (`output.io_mode`: serial_gather / parallel_collective / file_per_rank) — do NOT combine collective parallel writes with gzip filters unless verified
- Checkpoint/restart: atomic via temp-file + `rename(2)` (or SWMR); the previous good checkpoint survives a mid-write crash; checkpoints record config hash / git SHA (P3/P7 of `INTEGRATED_PLAN.md`)

