## 📌 Phase 8 Status — COMPLETE (solute transport solver; P8 → P16 gate OPEN)

P8 implements the **standalone solute (passive-scalar) advection–diffusion solver**. Clean
zero-warning `-Werror` build; **56/56 ctest pass** (43 cpu + 13 mpi); both seam checks pass;
P8→P16 gate OPEN. The solver is invoked from unit-test drivers only — the Orchestrator does
**not** call it yet (that wiring is P16). Implemented in `src/solute/` (`Frehg2::solute`,
**no PETSc types** — links core/io/decomp only; diffusion goes through the
`SparseSystem`/`LinearSolver` seam). Carry-forward facts:

- **`conc` lives in the P2 state classes**: `State::conc` (halo-padded surface,
  `Grid::getSurfaceIndex`) and `GwState::conc` (halo-padded 3D, `Grid::getIndex`), default 0.
  These are the canonical fields; `SoluteStepper` bridges device↔host work buffers (plain
  serial loops — Kokkos-ification is the single global P9 pass per DP3).
- **Advection** (`Advection.cpp`, `advectSurface`/`advectSubsurface`): conservative
  finite-volume **upwind** (default) + minmod **MUSCL** option (`solute.advection_scheme`);
  closed (zero-flux) outer boundaries ⇒ exact cell-sum conservation. CFL = sum of OUTGOING
  face fluxes; if `> cfl_max` the step is **refused** (field left unchanged). At unit Courant
  the upwind update is an exact one-cell shift (used as a machine-precision test).
- **Diffusion** (`Diffusion.cpp`, `DiffusionSolver`): implicit `(I − dt·D·L)` Neumann
  Laplacian (5-pt surface / 7-pt subsurface), SPD, solved via `LinearSolver` (cg+jacobi
  locally). Assembly emits COO via `SparseSystem::addRow`; PETSc staging stays in the backend.
- **Source/sink** (`SourceSink.cpp`): rainfall as mass-conservative **mixing**
  `C←(h·C+dt·R·c_rain)/(h+dt·R)` (drives C→c_rain at steady state; bounded generalization of
  the legacy first-order add); interface infiltration mixing; first-order decay `exp(-k·dt)`.
- **`SoluteStepper`** order = source/sink → advect → diffuse → record; signature
  `step(State&, GwState&, const SoluteFlow&, dt, rain)` (`SoluteFlow` = halo-padded face
  velocities/Darcy fluxes/depth/wc; replaces the plan's non-existent `FlowFields`).
  `solute.enabled=false` ⇒ immediate no-op (no PETSc assembly).
- **`SoluteParams::fromConfig`** parses the YAML `solute:` block (defaults: enabled=false,
  c_rain=0, k_decay=0, D=1e-9, advection_scheme=upwind, diffusion_scheme=implicit,
  cfl_max=1.0, min_depth=1e-8).
- Tests live in `tests/solute/` (repo mirrors `src/`, not the plan's `tests/unit` +
  `tests/integration`): `test_solute_state`, `test_advection`, `test_diffusion`,
  `test_source_sink`, `test_solute_stepper`, `test_yaml_solute`. The PETSc-using ones
  (`test_diffusion`, `test_solute_stepper`) init Kokkos+MPI+PETSc in their own `main`.

## 📌 Phase 11 Status — COMPLETE (async SW↔GW coupling pipeline; P11 → P12 gate PASSED)

P11 promotes the P6 blocking-sync coupling to a **double-buffered async pipeline** in the
Orchestrator, opt-in via `coupling.mode: async` (default `sequential`). Clean zero-warning
`-Werror` build; **57/57 ctest pass**; both seam checks pass; P11→P12 gate PASSED. Carry-forward
facts:

- **b1-sw / b2-gw are single-module** (SW-only / GW-only) and therefore **never enter the
  coupling path** — async cannot change them (`Orchestrator::asyncActive()` is false when not
  coupled). So the meaningful gate is a **COUPLED `sync` vs `async`** comparison; b1/b2 just prove
  async opt-in is regression-safe for single-module runs.
- **Bit-identical, not merely 1e-10**: the async path runs the identical Gauss–Seidel sequence
  (SW advance → exchange → GW catch-up); it only overlaps the GW catch-up of the *previous* window
  (on a worker thread) with the SW advance of the current window. Those touch disjoint
  `SweFields`/`GwFields` and both depend only on the already-applied exchange, so the result is
  bit-identical (`max|Δeta|`, `max|Δwc|`, `Δexchange_volume` all `< 1e-12`; rel-L2 `< 1e-10`).
  Gate: `tests/integration/test_async_coupling.cpp` (two coupled scenarios + the single-module
  regression-safety check).
- **`src/driver/DoubleBuffer.hpp`** — two `CouplingWindow` slots (leading = SW window, trailing =
  GW window) + `swap()`. **Deviation:** it double-buffers the coupling *time windows*, NOT copies
  of `State`/`GwState` (each solver already owns its fields; SW never reads in-flight GW state).
- **`src/driver/AsyncPipeline.{hpp,cpp}`** — `advanceWindow()` launches GW catch-up of the
  trailing window on a `std::thread` while SW advances the leading window on the caller, joins,
  then `applyExchange`. `drain()` finishes the pending GW window (idempotent); the Orchestrator
  drains before every output/checkpoint and at run end. Driven only via callbacks behind the
  `LinearSolver` seam — **no PETSc type, no GPU-bridge symbol**.
- **PETSc shared-comm safety**: the SW/GW `KSPSolve` calls are serialized by
  `Orchestrator::solve_mu_` (PETSc on a shared communicator is not thread-safe). The path is
  validated **single rank**; **multi-rank async falls back to synchronous coupling** (warned once
  in `initialize`). True concurrent solves await the **P10 (Task 10.3.7)** `PetscSubcomm` +
  CUDA/HIP-stream split, designed in **`docs/research_notes/async_gpu.md`**. CPU perf is therefore
  not improved yet (not a gate; P21 revisits).
- **`Orchestrator`**: `CouplingMode { Sequential, Async }`; `runLoop()` dispatches to
  `runLoopAsyncCoupled()` only when async + coupled + single-rank, else `runLoopSequential()`.
  Public `step()` keeps its synchronous fully-advanced semantics (direct callers/tests unaffected);
  `step()` and the pipeline share `swAdvanceTo`/`gwCatchUpTo`/`applyCouplingExchange` so both
  execute identical ops.

## 📌 Phase 12 Status — COMPLETE (polygon BC & source/sink; P12 → P13 gate PASSED)

P12 adds **polygon-based boundary conditions and source/sink regions** (from scratch — legacy
`frehg` has rectangular BCs only). Clean `-Werror` build, **62/62 ctest** (5 new), both seam
checks pass, b1-sw/b2-gw regressions unchanged. New library `frehg2_bc` (`Frehg2::bc`), wired
into the Orchestrator. Carry-forward facts:

- **Module layout**: the plan's `geometry/ + bcs/ + sources/` are consolidated into **`src/bc/`**
  (one lib): `Polygon.hpp` (header-only even-odd ray-casting + bbox reject),
  `PolygonRegion.{hpp,cpp}` (enums `BcKind{Discharge,Depth,Critical}` /
  `SourceKind{InflowRate,RainfallRate,ExtractionWell}`), `PolygonIndex.{hpp,cpp}`,
  `PolygonBC.{hpp,cpp}`, `PolygonSource.{hpp,cpp}`, `PolygonConfig.{hpp,cpp}`. Tests in
  `tests/bc/`. `frehg2_bc` has **no PETSc types** (drives SWE/RE via public field accessors).
- **No P2 `Domain`**: `PolygonIndex::build(polys, Grid, MpiComm*, x0, y0)` maps each OWNED column
  centroid `(x0+(gi+0.5)dx, y0+(gj+0.5)dy)` (`gi,gj` via `MpiComm::localToGlobal`; serial =
  identity) to the first containing polygon. Keyed by halo-padded surface index. Even-distribution
  denominators are GLOBAL per-polygon counts (`globalColumnCounts` → `MPI_Allreduce`).
  `domain.x0/y0` default 0.
- **Application timing**: BC/source are explicit **post-solve** state updates (matches the SWE
  solver's explicit rain/evap in `evaprain`, which runs AFTER the KSP solve — NOT "before solve").
  Surface regions fold into `Orchestrator::swAdvanceTo`; subsurface wells into `gwCatchUpTo`, so
  they apply on sequential AND async paths and in SW-only / GW-only runs. `updateDepth()`/
  `updateGeometry()` refresh after surface edits. **No-op when no polygons** ⇒ b1/b2 bit-identical.
- **Rules**: `bc_discharge` Q [m³/s] (>0 outflow, clamped to available; <0 inflow unlimited);
  `bc_depth` overrides eta; `bc_critical` weir `sqrt(g) h^{3/2} min(dx,dy)`; `inflow_rate`
  even-spread; `rainfall_rate` masked rainfall; `extraction_well` water-content sink at the
  deepest GW cell, clamped at `theta_r`. Schema is additive: `boundaries:` / `sources:`
  **sequences** of `{name,type,vertices,rate}`; the scalar `sources:` MAP (uniform rain/evap) is
  untouched (parser only reads a `sources:` sequence as polygons).
- **Gate**: `tests/integration/test_polygon_bc.cpp` — channel `bc_discharge` outlet drains exactly
  `Q` (accumulated outflow == `Q·t_end` to < 1e-6); inflow+outflow volumes both == `rate·t_end`.

